Scholastic, Inc.&nbsp; Thefirst was the <b><i>Scholastic Phonics Readers,</i></b> a 12 CD set ofinteractive stories and activities. Scholastic provided the assets, whileI provided the technical design and either completed or managed the programming.&nbsp;I developed an engine in <b>Director</b> which brought together databaseinformation and graphic and audio assets to produce a director file foreach portion of the program.&nbsp; This approach enabled us to producea set of 12 CDs, encompassing 72 stories, 216 activities, 72 tests, anda teacher managment section, and using approximately 26000 assets, in slightlyless than a year.&nbsp;<br>Another programmer and I also developed the management portion of theproduct in Director.&nbsp; This included the student login and teachermanagement section, which used the v12 database xtra to keep track of studentactivity.&nbsp;<br>In addition to programming the product itself in <b>Director</b>, Icreated or managed the creation of several production utilities in <b>C++</b>and<b>Quicktime</b>,<b>Director</b>, Delphi, and <b>perl</b>.<br>Following the <b><i>Phonics Readers,</i></b> we developed the<b><i>ScholasticPhonicsBooster Books,</i></b>an 8 CD set of 36 additional readers and activities.</td></tr></table></center><h3><img SRC="graphics/180logo_sm.GIF" NOSAVE BORDER=0 height=68 width=212 align=LEFT>Read180 Demo</h3>In 1999, Scholastic hired me to create the <b><i>Read 180 Demo</i></b>.&nbsp;I programmed the demo in <b>Director.</b>&nbsp; This was a fully interactivedemo that allowed the user to test each part of the actual program.&nbsp;I used marked audio and a database of word decodings to generate the phonicsportion of the demo.&nbsp; I also developed a number of production utilitiesto assist the Scholastic Team in creating the Read 180 assets.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<h3>Speech Recognition Prototype</h3>In 1999, I developed for Scholastic a prototype for a speech recognitionproduct, in which they tested the idea of using speech recognition technologyto give students feedback on their reading skills.&nbsp; I created thisproduct for Windows, using <b>VC++</b>, IBM's ViaVoice engine, Lernoutand Hauspie's engine.<br>&nbsp;<div ALIGN=right><h3>Feralette Records Website&nbsp;&nbsp;<img SRC="Fe.gif" NOSAVE BORDER=0 height=37 width=37 align=RIGHT></h3></div><div align=right>I developed www.feralette.com for Feralette Records, anindependent record label, in 2000.&nbsp; Feralette provided the graphicsand I put together the site using HTML.</div><h3>M@xracks Website</h3>Maxracks hired me to port www.maxracks.com, an e-card site, from a Macto a unix server.&nbsp; It was a complex website, using a 4th Dimensiondatabase server to log users, store an addressbook for each user, and generatea pict&nbsp;<a href="http://www.maxracks.com" TARGET="_blank"><img SRC="max_logo_small.gif" BORDER=0 height=52 width=100 align=LEFT></a>fileon the fly that combined an image the user had chosen with a message fromthe user, a stamp, and an email address.&nbsp; I recreated the site forunix using <b>perl</b> as the CGI language, and <b>mSQL</b> as the databaseserver.&nbsp; I also reprogrammed their redesigned home page in HTML andjavascript.&nbsp; I finished the port in 1999.&nbsp; In 2002, they hiredme again to upgrade their site to new versions of the perl GD module, andto switch from mSQL to <b>mySQL</b> as the database server.</td><td VALIGN=TOP><div ALIGN=right><h4>Projects</h4></div><div align=right><tt>Interactive Phonics</tt><br><tt>Maxracks Site</tt><br><tt>Feralette Site</tt><br><tt>Seaquest Game</tt><br><tt>HyperTV Browser Plugin</tt><br><tt>TenCORE</tt><br><tt>Speech Recognition Prototype</tt><br><tt>Read 180</tt><br><tt>eSchool ActiveX Control</tt><br><tt>Numbers and Letters CD</tt><br><tt>Fun With Science</tt><br><tt>A Field Trip to the Sky</tt><br><tt>Brain Builders</tt><br><tt>Thinking Machines</tt><br><tt>Priority Credit Exchange</tt><br><tt>Cosmic Encounter</tt><br><tt>DFi</tt><br><tt>SyncLips</tt><br><tt>CUNY Math Survey</tt><br><tt>IBM's Explore Series</tt><br><tt>StoryBook Theater</tt><br><tt>Explore-a-Story</tt><br><tt>Stage One</tt></div></td></tr></table><center><p>Here is a sampling of projects I have worked on.&nbsp; For a more completelisting, check out my <a href="resume.html">resume</a>.</center><p><br><center><table WIDTH="540" ><tr><td VALIGN=CENTER><a href="http://teacher.scholastic.com/ips/discover.htm" TARGET="_blank"><img SRC="logo_main.gif" HSPACE=8 VSPACE=2 BORDER=0 height=31 width=250 align=LEFT></a>Irecently completed a series of projects for Scholastic, Inc.&nbsp; Theseincluded the Scholastic Phonics Readers, a 12 CD set of 72 interactivestories and activities.&nbsp; I programmed the product entirely in Director,creating production utilities in C, Director, perl, and Delphi.&nbsp; FollowingIPR, we developed the Scholastic Phonics Booster Books, an 8 CD set ofadditional readers and activities, using the same strategy.</td></tr></table></center><br>&nbsp;<center><table COLS=2 WIDTH="500" ><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM WIDTH="60"><a href="http://www.maxracks.com" TARGET="_blank"><img SRC="max_logo_small.gif" BORDER=0 height=52 width=100></a></td></tr></table></center><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<center><table COLS=2 WIDTH="520" ><tr><td><center><h2><a href="treasure/index.html"><img SRC="Sqlogo.gif" BORDER=0 height=93 width=289></a></h2></center></td><td VALIGN=TOP><center><h2>Flat</h2></center>I programmed a shockwave game for Flat, Inc, that they developed as partof Addison-Wesley's Knowledge Adventure Online series.&nbsp; This is aseagoing adventure game... check it out.</td></tr></table></center><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<center><table COLS=2 WIDTH="500" ><tr><td VALIGN=TOP><center><h2>Boing!</h2></center><div align=right>As part-owner and technical designer for Boing!, LLC,I designed and prog